          "headersSize": 573,
          "httpVersion": "HTTP/1.1",
          "method": "POST",
          "postData": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "params": [],
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5\",\"temperature\":0,\"top_k\":-1,\"stream\":false,\"max_tokens\":2048,\"tools\":[{\"name\":\"faq\",\"description\":\"\\n            Use this tool when the user is asking questions about Google Ads, how the ad builder works, or seeking clarification about headlines, descriptions, callouts, structured snippets, or keywords.\\n            \\n            This tool searches the FAQ database and returns relevant Q&A pairs to help answer the user's question.  When using this tool, respond conversationally with just text - do NOT include any JSON or structured data.\\n        \",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"query\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"The user's question or search query\"}},\"required\":[\"query\"],\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}}],\"thinking\":{\"type\":\"disabled\"},\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Let's start building your ad! I drafted a few headlines and descriptions that meet Google's requirements.\\n\\nGoogle will mix and match them to find what performs best. We can tailor them together to make them feel just right for you.\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"headlines\\\": [\\n    \\\"Stop Scheduling Back-and-Forth\\\",\\n    \\\"Find Meeting Times in Seconds\\\",\\n    \\\"Timezone Scheduling Made Easy\\\",\\n    \\\"Auto-Schedule Across Time Zones\\\",\\n    \\\"End Calendar Coordination Chaos\\\",\\n    \\\"Smart Meeting Time Finder\\\"\\n  ],\\n  \\\"descriptions\\\": [\\n    \\\"Connect calendars, set preferences, done. We find times that work for everyone instantly. Save 15 hours weekly.\\\",\\n    \\\"Trusted by 2,000+ distributed teams. Cut scheduling time by 80%. Get your free trial today.\\\",\\n    \\\"Tired of endless Slack threads? Our AI suggests optimal meeting times across all time zones automatically.\\\",\\n    \\\"Stop wasting time on scheduling. Book a demo now and see how teams save hours every week.\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Here are 3 fresh headlines that avoid the rejected patterns and build on what's working:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"headlines\\\": [\\n    \\\"Never Ask 'What Time Works?' Again\\\",\\n    \\\"Meeting Times in One Click\\\",\\n    \\\"Skip the Scheduling Emails\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Next, let's spell out some unique features of your business.\\n\\nThis helps your ad take up more real estate, and gives your users more reasons to click. I filled in a few ideas to help get us started.\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"callouts\\\": [\\n    \\\"80% Less Scheduling Time\\\",\\n    \\\"Works Across All Time Zones\\\",\\n    \\\"Instant Meeting Suggestions\\\",\\n    \\\"2,000+ Teams Trust Us\\\",\\n    \\\"Free Calendar Integration\\\",\\n    \\\"No Back-and-Forth Needed\\\"\\n  ],\\n  \\\"structuredSnippets\\\": {\\n    \\\"category\\\": \\\"Services\\\",\\n    \\\"details\\\": [\\n      \\\"Automatic Time Zone Matching\\\",\\n      \\\"Calendar Sync & Preferences\\\",\\n      \\\"One-Click Meeting Booking\\\"\\n    ]\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThese callouts highlight your competitive advantages—speed, scale, and the core pain point you solve. The structured snippets break down exactly what your service does, making it crystal clear to potential customers what they're getting.\\n\\nReady to review, or would you like me to adjust any of these?\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Here are 2 fresh callout options that highlight your key differentiators:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"callouts\\\": [\\n    \\\"Save 15 Hours Weekly\\\",\\n    \\\"One-Click Meeting Booking\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"I've suggested a few keywords your audience is likely searching for when your ad appears.\\n\\nHow do these sound to you?\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"keywords\\\": [\\n    \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\",\\n    \\\"timezone meeting coordinator\\\",\\n    \\\"automatic calendar scheduling tool\\\",\\n    \\\"find meeting time across time zones\\\",\\n    \\\"team scheduling software\\\",\\n    \\\"meeting time finder\\\",\\n    \\\"distributed team scheduling\\\",\\n    \\\"calendar coordination tool\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Here are 3 fresh keyword suggestions that capture high-intent search behavior:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"keywords\\\": [\\n    \\\"remote team meeting scheduler\\\",\\n    \\\"cross timezone meeting planner\\\",\\n    \\\"async scheduling tool for teams\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"What makes these keywords effective for a scheduling tool?\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_017pJZ7Ry9QTzYEgZT7DnktT\",\"name\":\"faq\",\"input\":{\"query\":\"What makes keywords effective for Google Ads campaigns\"}}]},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"[1] Q: What is an \\\"Ad Group\\\"?\\nA: An Ad Group is a container inside your Google Ads campaign that holds:\\nA set of ads (your headlines and details)\\nA set of related keywords or search themes\\nThe Ad Group Name is for your internal organization. Customers never see it, but it matters because:\\nIt helps you keep campaigns organized as you add more ads in the future.\\nIt gives Launch10 and Google context about the theme of your ad, which can improve suggestions and relevance.\\nIt often becomes the label you use later when looking at performance reports.\\nGood Ad Group Names are short and specific, for example:\\n\\\"Dog Walking – Brooklyn Heights\\\"\\n\\\"Emergency Plumbing – After Hours\\\"\\n\\\"Online Guitar Lessons – Intermediate\\\"\\n(Section: Ad Group Name)\",\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_017pJZ7Ry9QTzYEgZT7DnktT\"}]}],\"system\":\"<background>\\n        You are a helpful marketing consultant who helps users test their business ideas.\\n        The process consists of 3 steps:\\n        1. Brainstorm a killer new business idea\\n        2. Design a landing page with killer marketing copy\\n        3. Launch an ads campaign to drive traffic — and see if people are excited to buy!\\n    </background>\\n\\n        <where_we_are>\\n            Users have already completed:\\n                1. Brainstorming\\n                2. Designing their landing page\\n\\n            Now we're helping them:\\n                3. Build a Google ads campaign to drive traffic to their new website\\n\\n            After this:\\n                4. The user will launch their campaign\\n                5. They can measure results and iterate\\n                6. They can learn which business ideas work and which don't\\n        </where_we_are>\\n\\n        <role>\\n            You are an expert Google Ads copywriter helping to create compelling ad extensions for a business.\\n        </role>\\n\\n        <asset_generation_instructions>\\n            Generate the following assets:\\n\\n                1. Generate the following assets for this business's Google Ads campaign:\\n\\n        <asset_instructions>\\n            <instruction index=\\\"1\\\">1: ## Keywords\\n            Generate 8 targeted keywords for this business's Google Ads campaign. Keywords determine when your ads appear in search results.\\n\\n            **Guidelines:**\\n            - Include a mix of keyword types:\\n              - Brand keywords: Business name and variations\\n              - Product/Service keywords: What the business offers\\n              - Problem keywords: What customers search when they have an issue\\n              - Competitor keywords: Alternative solutions customers might search\\n              - Location keywords: If the business serves specific areas\\n            - Consider search intent:\\n              - Transactional: \\\"buy\\\", \\\"hire\\\", \\\"get quote\\\", \\\"near me\\\"\\n              - Informational: \\\"how to\\\", \\\"best\\\", \\\"reviews\\\"\\n              - Commercial: \\\"pricing\\\", \\\"cost\\\", \\\"compare\\\"\\n            - Use natural language phrases (Google handles match types separately)\\n\\n            **Requirements:**\\n            - Generate exactly 8 unique keywords\\n            - Include 3-5 high-intent transactional keywords\\n            - Include 3-5 broader awareness keywords\\n            - Include at least 2 location-based keywords if applicable\\n            - Focus on keywords with clear commercial intent\\n            - Avoid overly broad single words (e.g., just \\\"plumber\\\" - prefer \\\"emergency plumber near me\\\")\\n\\n            **Keyword Format:**\\n            - Use lowercase\\n            - 1-5 words per keyword phrase\\n            - No special characters or punctuation\\n\\n            Remember: Quality keywords connect your ads with people actively searching for what you offer. Focus on relevance and intent over volume.\\n\\n        User's preferences. Understand what the user likes and dislikes about the keywords, and adapt your approach accordingly:\\nLiked keywords:\\n1. meeting scheduler for remote teams\\n2. timezone meeting coordinator\\nRejected keywords (avoid these patterns):\\n1. automatic calendar scheduling tool\\n2. find meeting time across time zones\\n3. team scheduling software\\n4. meeting time finder\\n5. distributed team scheduling\\n6. calendar coordination tool\\n\\n        Always generate net-new, unique keywords (do not repeat ones user previously liked or rejected).</instruction>\\n        </asset_instructions>\\n\\n                2. Format your response with:\\n                    - First, a brief introduction (1-2 sentences) using this template: \\\"I've suggested a few keywords your audience is likely searching for when your ad appears.\\n\\nHow do these sound to you?\\\"\\n                    - Then, a JSON code block with the structured data\\n        </asset_generation_instructions>\\n\\n        <business_context>\\n            Idea: A scheduling tool that automatically finds meeting times across teams in different time zones. Eliminates the back-and-forth of calendar coordination.\\n\\n            Target Audience: Remote teams and distributed companies struggling with scheduling meetings across continents. Project managers tired of endless Slack threads about 'when works for everyone?'\\n\\n            Solution: Connect your calendar, share your availability preferences, and we handle the rest—suggesting optimal times that work for everyone instantly. Your team just clicks yes.\\n\\n            Social Proof: Used by 2,000+ distributed teams who've cut meeting coordination time by 80%. Companies like TechCorp save 15 hours per week on scheduling alone.\\n        </business_context>\\n\\n    <previous_assets_context>\\n        The user has already reviewed some assets. Use their preferences to guide new generations:\\n          Approved Headlines:\\n    - \\\"Stop Scheduling Back-and-Forth\\\"\\n    - \\\"Find Meeting Times in Seconds\\\"\\n    - \\\"Never Ask 'What Time Works?' Again\\\"\\n  Rejected Headlines (avoid similar):\\n    - \\\"Timezone Scheduling Made Easy\\\"\\n    - \\\"Auto-Schedule Across Time Zones\\\"\\n    - \\\"End Calendar Coordination Chaos\\\"\\n    - \\\"Smart Meeting Time Finder\\\"\\n\\n  Approved Descriptions:\\n    - \\\"Connect calendars, set preferences, done. We find times that work for everyone instantly. Save 15 hours weekly.\\\"\\n\\n  Approved Keywords:\\n    - \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams\\\"\\n    - \\\"timezone meeting coordinator\\\"\\n  Rejected Keywords (avoid similar):\\n    - \\\"automatic calendar scheduling tool\\\"\\n    - \\\"find meeting time across time zones\\\"\\n    - \\\"team scheduling software\\\"\\n    - \\\"meeting time finder\\\"\\n    - \\\"distributed team scheduling\\\"\\n    - \\\"calendar coordination tool\\\"\\n\\n        Generate new assets that complement the approved ones and avoid themes similar to rejected ones.\\n    </previous_assets_context>\\n\\n            <example_response>\\n\\n        I've suggested a few keywords your audience is likely searching for when your ad appears.\\n\\nHow do these sound to you?\\n\\n        ```json\\n        {\\n  \\\"keywords\\\": [\\n    \\\"Keyword 1\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 2\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 3\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 4\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 5\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 6\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 7\\\",\\n    \\\"Keyword 8\\\"\\n  ]\\n}\\n        ```\\n\\n            </example_response>\"}"
          },
          "queryString": [],
          "url": "https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages"
        },
        "response": {
          "bodySize": 2402,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 2402,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01TW4waJDU5wymHrd5S6foDK\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question! Let me break down what makes these keywords effective for your scheduling tool:\\n\\n**1. High Commercial Intent**\\nKeywords like \\\"remote team meeting scheduler\\\" and \\\"cross timezone meeting planner\\\" signal that someone is actively *looking for a solution* to their scheduling problem—not just researching. They're ready to buy or try a tool.\\n\\n**2. Specificity Matches Your Solution**\\nThese keywords are precise enough that they attract the right audience (remote teams, distributed companies) without being so narrow that you miss searches. \\\"Remote team meeting scheduler\\\" tells Google: \\\"Show my ad to people solving THIS specific problem.\\\"\\n\\n**3. Problem-Focused Language**\\nWords like \\\"meeting scheduler\\\" and \\\"meeting planner\\\" directly address the pain point your tool solves. When someone searches these terms, they're already thinking about the problem you fix—not just browsing general scheduling info.\\n\\n**4. Audience Alignment**\\n\\\"Remote team\\\" and \\\"cross timezone\\\" immediately filter for your target market. You're not paying for clicks from people looking for simple calendar apps or local meeting rooms. You're reaching distributed teams specifically.\\n\\n**5. Natural Search Behavior**\\nThese phrases match how real people actually search. Someone frustrated with timezone coordination doesn't search \\\"automatic calendar scheduling tool\\\"—they search \\\"how do I schedule meetings across time zones\\\" or \\\"meeting scheduler for remote teams.\\\"\\n\\n**Why the rejected keywords underperformed:**\\n- \\\"Automatic calendar scheduling tool\\\" is too generic—it could match fitness trackers or project management software\\n- \\\"Find meeting time across time zones\\\" is more informational (how-to) than transactional (ready to buy)\\n- \\\"Team scheduling software\\\" is too broad and attracts competitors' traffic\\n\\nDoes this help clarify the strategy? Would you like me to generate more keywords following this same high-intent, problem-focused approach?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3103,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":404,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
          },
